      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Top Scoring Two-Letter Words</h2>
      <p>When you need maximum points from minimal tiles, these are your best options:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>QI — 11 points:</strong> The undisputed champion. Q (10) + I (1). The only two-letter Q word.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZA — 11 points:</strong> Z (10) + A (1). Pizza slang that saves your game when you draw Z.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZO — 11 points:</strong> Z (10) + O (1). A Tibetan yak hybrid. SOWPODS only.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>XI, XU — 9 points each:</strong> X (8) + vowel (1). Two ways to dump your X for big points.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>AX, EX, OX — 9 points each:</strong> Vowel (1) + X (8). Three more X options, played in reverse.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>JA, JO — 9 points each:</strong> J (8) + vowel (1). Useful for dumping your J quickly.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>KY — 9 points:</strong> K (5) + Y (4). Scottish word for cows. SOWPODS only.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">How to Use This List</h2>
      <p>The best approach to memorising two-letter words is to work through them in groups rather than trying to learn all 127 at once. Start with the high-value words (QI, ZA, XI, XU, ZO) since they come up less often but have the biggest impact when they do. Then learn the common vowel combinations (AA, AE, AI, OE, OI) that let you play alongside existing words.</p>
      <p>Practice by looking at the board during games and asking yourself: "What two-letter words could I form if I played parallel to that word?" Over time, the patterns become automatic. Many tournament players report that learning the two-letter words added 30-50 points to their average game score.</p>
      <p>For instant verification during practice, use our <a href="/" class="text-blue-400 hover:underline">word finder tool</a> — type any two letters and see immediately whether they form a valid word.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">SOWPODS vs TWL: Which Words Count?</h2>
      <p>The SOWPODS dictionary (used internationally) contains 127 two-letter words, while the TWL (used in North American tournaments) contains 107. Words like CH, FY, GU, IO, JA, KO, KY, OO, OU, ST, ZO and others are valid in SOWPODS but not in TWL. Always check which dictionary your game or tournament uses before relying on these words.</p>
      <p>If you're playing online (Words With Friends, Scrabble GO, etc.), the accepted word list may differ from both official dictionaries. Our word finder uses the SOWPODS list by default, giving you the broadest possible reference.</p>

